			<div class="content" id="post-content-2829211">
									

<blockquote>
<p>because they're basically just there to demonstrate how dangerous these things are.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Which is why it seems shallow. That's one thing that I think would improve this. You also have the option of slowing down the pacing and adding detail into the roaches 'evolution'.</p>
<p>We didn't see any that adapted to, say, the security personnel that may have been present on-site. I think it'd have been as helluva lot more eerie for the first few roaches they come across simply cry for help/beg for mercy - no immediate danger, just plain mindfuck-horror. The introduction of security-roaches would serve to escalate the situation from there.</p>
<p>Consider also that the instances serve as small 'snapshots' of the events that had transpired over the course of the breach. There is <em>so</em> much that could be milked from that.</p>
<p>The opportunity for misdirection, too, is present. I could see them becoming increasingly paranoid as every time they attempt to track down a survivor, it's another 3035. Perhaps they come across a makeshift barricade, thinking they found someone, but it's 3035 that copied the behavior? What about when they begin copying the MTF themselves (and what if they got split up?)?</p>
<p>Someone on the 3035 discussion also mentioned othe SCPs on-site. That might be another thread to follow. What are/is they/it? Could there be more hints as to what had originally affected the roaches? Could you count a humanoid skip amongst the desperate survivors/mimicked dead?</p>
<p>Right now, this is alright - not bad, but considering your ability, it could be amazing.</p>

